  "response_text": "The Pythagorean theorem is a fundamental concept in geometry that describes the relationship between the lengths of the sides of a right-angled triangle. It states that:\n\n**a\u00b2 + b\u00b2 = c\u00b2**\n\nwhere:\n\n- **a** is the length of the base (or one of the shorter sides)\n- **b** is the length of the height (or the other shorter side)\n- **c** is the length of the hypotenuse (the longest side, opposite the right angle)\n\nThis theorem works because it is a mathematical representation of the way that the sides of a right-angled triangle relate to each other. The theorem is named after the ancient Greek philosopher and mathematician Pythagoras, who is credited with its discovery.\n\n**Why does it work?**\n\nThe Pythagorean theorem works because it is based on the concept of similar triangles and the properties of squares. When you square the lengths of the two shorter sides (a and b) and add them together, you",
